body:
(tested with the latest Insider's Build: 1ab254dde53)

With the Haxe extension, there's some situations where completion items are ranked in a counter-intuitive fashion. Here's a simple completion provider to reproduce:

```ts
'use strict';
import * as vscode from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    vscode.languages.registerCompletionItemProvider('plaintext', {
        provideCompletionItems(doc, pos, token, context) {
            var range = new vscode.Range(new vscode.Position(0, 0), pos);
            return [
                {label: "Button - ui.Button", range: range},
                {label: "Button - hl.UI.Button", range: range}
            ];
        }
    });
}
```

Entering `ui.Button` results in the following sorting order:

![](https://i.imgur.com/7uyIdHh.png)

This is counter-intuitive to me for at least two reasons:

- `ui.Button` is an _exact_ match for a substring in the second item, yet it's ranked lower. I guess it's case-insensitive, but maybe it shouldn't be? :)
- Even apart from that, the match in the second case comes earlier in the string - shouldn't that lead to it ranking higher?
